–Male":"1375–Deceased","1376–Female":"1376–Deceased","1397–Female":"1397–Deceased","1339–Male":"1339–Deceased","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1455":"1455","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","1397":"1397","1396":"1396","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Ilcombe, Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","East Down, Devon, England":"East Down, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Luccombe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon): habitational name from any of the five villages of this name in Devon or from Loscombe in Powerstock, Dorset, all probably named from Old English <i>hlōse</i> ‘pigsty’ + <i>cumb</i> ‘valley’ (see   Coombe  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Luscomb","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Luscombe  ."]},{"name":"Coombe","meanings":["English (Devon and Cornwall):","topographic name from Middle English <i>combe</i> (Old English <i>cumb</i>, of Celtic origin) denoting a bowl-shaped valley, or else a habitational name from a place so named. A large number of places in southwestern England, mostly spelled <i>Combe</i>, are named with this word.","nickname from Middle English <i>come</i> (Old English <i>cuma</i>) ‘guest, stranger, newcomer’. Compare   Coombs  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":80,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Luccombe was born in 1375, in Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England, his father, John Luccombe, was 36 and his mother, Margaret Kayle, was 25. He married Phillipa Kellaways in 1396, in Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1375–":"1375–Surnud","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1376–Female":"1376–Surnud","1397–Female":"1397–Surnud","1339–Male":"1339–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1455":"1455","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","1397":"1397","1396":"1396","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1339":"1339","Ilcombe, Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","East Down, Devon, England":"East Down, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1375–":"1375–Kuollut","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1376–Female":"1376–Kuollut","1397–